    "imputed_age_median = df_median['age']\n",
    "axes[2].hist(imputed_age_median, bins=20, alpha=0.7, color='orange', edgecolor='black')\n",
    "axes[2].axvline(imputed_age_median.median(), color='red', linestyle='--', linewidth=2, label=f'Median: {imputed_age_median.median():.1f}')\n",
    "axes[2].set_xlabel('Age')\n",
    "axes[2].set_ylabel('Frequency')\n",
    "axes[2].set_title('Median Imputed Age Distribution')\n",
    "axes[2].legend()\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 7. Understanding Duplicate Data\n",
    "\n",
    "Duplicate data occurs when the same entity or attribute appears multiple times in a dataset.\n",
    "\n",
    "| Type | Meaning |\n",
    "|------|---------|\n",
    "| Duplicate Rows | Same object repeated |\n",
    "| Duplicate Columns | Same attribute repeated |\n",
    "\n",
    "**Example:**\n",
    "\n",
    "| Name | Phone |\n",
    "|------|-------|\n",
    "| Ravi | 99999 |\n",
    "| Ravi | 99999 |\n",
    "\n",
    "Duplicate data inflates the dataset artificially and biases statistical analysis."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Create dataset with duplicates\n",
    "np.random.seed(42)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Base data\n",
    "customers = pd.DataFrame({\n",
    "    'customer_id': range(1, 51),\n",
    "    'name': [f'Customer_{i}' for i in range(1, 51)],\n",
    "    'email': [f'customer{i}@email.com' for i in range(1, 51)],\n",
    "    'phone': [f'99{i:04d}' for i in range(1, 51)],\n",
    "    'city': np.random.choice(['Mumbai', 'Delhi', 'Bangalore', 'Chennai'], 50),\n",
    "    'purchase_amount': np.random.randint(1000, 50000, 50)\n",
    "})\n",
    "\n",
    "# Add exact duplicates\n",
    "duplicates = customers.iloc[:5].copy()\n",
    "customers_with_dup = pd.concat([customers, duplicates], ignore_index=True)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Add near duplicates (slight variations)\n",
    "near_dup = customers.iloc[10:12].copy()\n",
    "near_dup['name'] = near_dup['name'].str.replace('Customer', 'Cust')\n",
    "near_dup['email'] = near_dup['email'].str.replace('@', '_at_')\n",
    "customers_with_dup = pd.concat([customers_with_dup, near_dup], ignore_index=True)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"DATASET WITH DUPLICATE RECORDS\")\n",
    "print(\"=\" * 40)\n",
    "print(f\"Original size: {len(customers)}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Size with duplicates: {len(customers_with_dup)}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Exact duplicates added: 5\")\n",
    "print(f\"Near duplicates added: 2\")\n",
    "print(\"\\nSample rows (showing duplicates):\")\n",
    "customers_with_dup.tail(15)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 8. Causes of Duplicate Data\n",
    "\n",
    "Duplicate records are usually introduced during **data integration**.\n",
    "\n",
    "Suppose multiple systems independently store customer records:\n",
    "- Banking System\n",
    "- Insurance Database\n",
    "- Government Records\n",
    "- Hospital Records\n",
    "\n",
    "When merged blindly, the same individual may appear multiple times with slight differences.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Example:**\n",
    "\n",
    "| Source | Name |\n",
    "|--------|------|\n",
    "| PAN Card | Heman R |\n",
    "| Voter ID | R Heman |\n",
    "| Passport | Heman Rathore |\n",
    "\n",
    "A naive merge may incorrectly treat these as different individuals."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Simulate data integration from multiple sources\n",
    "print(\"DATA INTEGRATION FROM MULTIPLE SOURCES\")\n",
    "print(\"=\" * 45)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Source 1: Banking System\n",
    "bank_data = pd.DataFrame({\n",
    "    'id': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5],\n",
    "    'name': ['Rajesh Kumar', 'Priya Singh', 'Amit Patel', 'Neha Gupta', 'Suresh Reddy'],\n",
    "    'account_type': ['Savings', 'Current', 'Savings', 'Savings', 'Current']\n",
    "})\n",
    "\n",
    "# Source 2: Insurance Database\n",
    "insurance_data = pd.DataFrame({\n",
    "    'id': [101, 102, 103, 104, 105],\n",
    "    'name': ['R. Kumar', 'Priya S.', 'Patel Amit', 'Neha G.', 'S. Reddy'],\n",
    "    'policy_type': ['Life', 'Health', 'Auto', 'Life', 'Health']\n",
    "})\n",
    "\n",
    "# Source 3: Government Records\n",
    "gov_data = pd.DataFrame({\n",
    "    'id': [1001, 1002, 1003, 1004, 1005],\n",
    "    'name': ['Rajesh K', 'Priya Singh', 'Amitbhai Patel', 'Neha Gupta', 'Suresh Reddy'],\n",
    "    'aadhaar': ['XXXX-1111', 'XXXX-2222', 'XXXX-3333', 'XXXX-4444', 'XXXX-5555']\n",
    "})\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"\\nBank Data:\")\n",
    "print(bank_data)\n",
    "print(\"\\nInsurance Data:\")\n",
    "print(insurance_data)\n",
    "print(\"\\nGovernment Data:\")\n",
    "print(gov_data)\n",
    "print(\"\\n\" + \"=\" * 45)\n",
    "print(\"These records represent the SAME individuals but with DIFFERENT identifiers!\")\n",
    "print(\"Merging naively would create duplicates.\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 9. Aadhaar Case Study and Data Integration\n",
    "\n",
    "The Aadhaar system is a real-world example of duplicate-data complexity.\n",
    "\n",
    "Before Aadhaar, India already had multiple identification systems:\n",
    "- PAN Card\n",
    "- Voter ID\n",
    "- Passport\n",
    "- Ration Card\n",
    "\n",
    "In theory, these databases could have been merged to identify citizens uniquely.\n",
    "\n",
    "However, inconsistencies across systems created severe duplication and integration challenges.\n",
    "\n",
